# Kubernetes Deployment Guide

These steps cover building container images and deploying the application to Kubernetes with the Helm chart in `employee-leave-management-chart/`.

## 1. Build and Push Images

1. Choose a tag, for example the current git SHA:
   ```sh
   export IMAGE_TAG=$(git rev-parse --short HEAD)
   ```
2. Build the backend image (Gunicorn-based):
   ```sh
   docker build -t cosminregistrydev.azurecr.io/employee-leave-backend:${IMAGE_TAG} backend
   docker push cosminregistrydev.azurecr.io/employee-leave-backend:${IMAGE_TAG}
   ```
3. Build the frontend image:
   ```sh
   docker build -t cosminregistrydev.azurecr.io/employee-leave-frontend:${IMAGE_TAG} frontend
   docker push cosminregistrydev.azurecr.io/employee-leave-frontend:${IMAGE_TAG}
   ```

## 2. Prepare Helm values

Update `employee-leave-management-chart/values.yaml` or create an override file to set:

- `backend.tag` and `frontend.tag` to `${IMAGE_TAG}`
- Any environment variables required by the backend under `backend.env`
- Secrets referenced by `backend.secretName`

Example override file (`values-prod.yaml`):

```yaml
backend:
  tag: "${IMAGE_TAG}"
frontend:
  tag: "${IMAGE_TAG}"
```

## 3. Deploy / Upgrade

Run Helm upgrade (namespace will be created if it does not exist):

```sh
kubectl create namespace employee-leave --dry-run=client -o yaml | kubectl apply -f -
helm upgrade --install employee-leave employee-leave-management-chart \
  --namespace employee-leave \
  --values employee-leave-management-chart/values.yaml \
  --values values-prod.yaml
```

## 4. Verify

- Pods should become `Ready`:
  ```sh
  kubectl get pods -n employee-leave
  ```
- Check the ingress:
  ```sh
  kubectl get ingress -n employee-leave
  ```
- Confirm Prometheus scraping via `ServiceMonitor` if the monitoring stack is installed.

## 5. Rollbacks

Helm keeps revision history, so you can roll back to the previous deployment:

```sh
helm rollback employee-leave 1 -n employee-leave
```
